            <h3>WWWCD</h3>
            <h4>What would Walter Capps do</h4>
            <hr>
            <p>On the first day of class, after the initial syllabus, we were introduced to Walter Capps. Or at least to the memory of Professor Capps, who started this ultra successful (and now quite famous) course at UCSB. Immediately I was very proud to hear that UCSB held the first official course on the Vietnam war, and a bit bummed out that I would not experience the same professor as the first class did many years ago (no offense meant to anyone!). Just as one of my favorite and recently deceased professors, Dr. Babcock, deserves the highest respects, it seems that Professor Capps did too. So of course I was excited to read his work, "<em>The Unfinished War: Vietnam and the American Conscience</em>". It seemed to align with the goal of the class, to examine the effects of the Vietnam war on individuals of both sides, and on our country as a whole. </p>
            <p>When learning about any American historical event, I need to start at the beginning with the historical context, as I am extremely unfamiliar with US history. <em>The Unfinished War</em> helped me with the context of the Vietnam war. In retrospect, I have done poorly in many of my history classes because the topics are massive and vague: "Western Civilization" or "The Middle Ages". I hope that focusing on a specific and modern event will help me finally learn something of true significance other than dates. And that is why I am taking this course, to <em>feel</em> something instead of just memorizing. Here is a list of things I hope to learn by the end of the quarter:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>The historical context of Vietnam and the US prior to the war.</li>
                <li>US and Vietnamese public opinion before the war.</li>
                <li>How young draftees and volunteers felt about the war.</li>
                <li>First hand account of the war, hopefully from both side.</li>
                <li>PTSD</li>
                <li>Long term effects of the war. Economic and Social.</li>
            </ol>
            <p>Hopefully these goals are aligned with what Walter Capps would want his students taking away from RS 155. There will probably be a long list of things I deem more valuable as the class progresses, and I hope to really learn from the first hand accounts in class.</p>
            <p><em>Update:</em> I found this interesting <a href="http://www.independent.com/news/2008/apr/10/keeping-representative-cappss-legacy-alive-ucsb/" target="_blank">article</a> on Professor Capps a few weeks after first writing this.</p>
        </div>

        <div id="2" class="writing">
            <h3>A Face of War</h3>
            <h4>Basic Info about the movie</h4>
            <hr>
            <p><em>Note:</em> This is the one writing I did (mostly) in class, I hoped to write down exactly when I was feeling - stream of consciousness style - as the movie played.</p>
            <p>The events described over a period of 97 days in Vietnam in the movie were raw and authentic. Immediately, the lack of background sound effects and music silently grabbed my attention. </p>
            <p>The first zoom in on the soldiers' faces showed that a few of them were very new, while the more confident soldiers had obviously been there a while.</p>
            <p>The initial explosion of noise and action brought the students into the battlefield with the wounded soldier. I've always <em>expected</em> a glorious death for myself, spending my last moments in a warm bed with a nice view...surrounded by friends and family. The fact that so many young men and women were robbed of a comfortable passing hurt me the most. Reminds me of my Grandpa again.</p>
            <p>The little things kept the soldiers going. This idea was echoed by one of the soldiers begging for an extra cigarette or magazine. What would I grab in my last minute? Would it be a person or thing? I'm not looking forward to finding out, though it would be interesting to know. </p>
            <p>The Helicopter scene reminded me of Wilson's accounts of his experience as a Chinook pilot. I can't grasp that he was my age, and now standing in from of me so much older.</p>
            <p>In 1965 they thought they were helping the Vietnamese from Communism. They fully believed that Communism was a world threat and needed to be stopped at any cost. Kennedy agreed to support the South Vietnamese Government, Johnson took office and escalated the war. They held sick call there every day. People flocked there to get medical attention form the soldiers. They were arrogant in the way they treated the Vietnamese villagers. They would just napalm the village to help prevent the VietCongs flow of supply. Killing someone seems too intense to grasp. I would try to hide from my guilt behind excuses.</p>
            <p>We were left with this question: <span class="red">If I didn't do anything wrong, then why do I feel I need to be forgiven?</span> </p>
        </div>

        <div id="3" class="writing">
            <h3>My First 25 Days in Vietnam</h3>
            <h4>A writing by Jim Nolan</h4>
            <hr>
            <p>Meeting the author of a story, the director of a movie, or the artist behind a piece makes the work exponentially more meaningful. I first 'met' Jim Nolan on the first day of class and at that point he was nothing more that a stranger. Over the next few weeks, I believe the entire class quickly grew to respect Jim Nolan. For the first time in a long time, I was looking forward to reading a homework assignment. While reading Jim Nolans account <em>My First 25 Days in Vietnam</em> I tried to keep in mind that <strong>he was the same age as me</strong> when it all happened.</p>
            <p>I've driven past the Camp Pendleton exit dozens of time, and the hot September day that Jim describes bring back recent memories of working in San Diego.</p>
            <p>Jim's story is about starting a new chapter of his life, and every new chapter begins with letting go. The last time I had to let go was leaving for college, where I knew I would be safe and could return home at any time. If I instead had to ship off to war, the butterflies in my stomach would have gotten the best of me. What it must have felt like to depart on the greatest and most dangerous adventure of his life.</p>
            <p>When I left on my great adventure (to college), my life changed dramatically. I met someone here who makes it difficult to image me not knowing her. Jim Nolan met Charlie Slager, the man who taught Jim how to sleep, walk, live and survive in Vietnam. The part of Jim's account that shows his love of Charlie was his volunteering to walk point. Its difficult to image wanting to prove yourself so badly that you risk your life. People always try to prove themselves to each other and build relationships, buts its very rarely a life or death matter. There must have been such a feeling of mutual respect amongst troops in the war. </p>
            <p>Jim spoke of camaraderie in he writing. As a child, I was always taught to work together and get along with my brother and cousins. We have a sense of camaraderie, as so my old football teammates and my current house mates. I know first hand that camaraderie is best build through mutual sacrifice and hard work...and it seems like war is the the ultimate bond builder.</p>
            <p></p>
        </div>
        <div id="4" class="writing">
            <h3>Harry - Captain</h3>
            <h4></h4>
            <hr>
            <p>Harry, like the other speakers, grew up with a history of service in his family...he "had an aspiration to follow [his] father." This is something I've been grappling with, trying to understand why some kids whose parents were never in the Military still want to go. I've had cousins who really wanted to be in the Army/Navy/Airforce, and I always thought it was because of video games. Video games and movies brainwashed my Brother and cousins into liking shooting and fighting and running around like an idiot fighting other people's battles. But that was just my opinion.</p>
            <p>I think I'm beginning to understand the need to serve that the children of Veterans feel. Especially those whose mother or father died in battle. My dad sacrificed years of his life for me, and thats enough to get me through a tough day, but he didn't die. I still get to see him every day. My life would not be the same without a father. Is sacrificing your life for your country fair? Personally, I would say f*ck the country...I need be there for my kids. But maybe once in a while being there for your kids means fighting in a war. Still, I couldn't see myself ever doing it, I'm too selfish. I want to experience a normal fun life, and I want all my family members and children to be safe for the entirety of their lives.</p>
            <p>I enjoyed that the Captain talked to us about his days at the Naval academy. He gave the first account of going through one of the academies and being of a high rank. The Naval academy expected performance and the meeting of set expectations. "Performance measurement was a religion at the academy." They spoke of <em>mental toughness</em>, to persevere in pursuit of a goal, no matter how long it takes or how much pain is involved.</p>
            <p></p>
