        <div id="5" class="writing">
            <h3>Kevin's off to the Air Force</h3>
            <h4>I just found out my brother will be attending the Air Force academy</h4>
            <hr>
            <p>I just found out my brother will be attending the Air Force academy, and I hate it. I like it too, and I'm happy for him. Years of hard work, and I mean very hard work, have opened doors for my younger brother. Kevin my quite, gentle, motivated little brother will be playing division 1 football for the United States Air Force Academy, and I'm scared. I hate that he'll be stressed, over worked, and away from my family.</p>
            <p>I hate that Kevin will be gone, just like my cousins when they went off to college. I hate that he'll be in Colorado when I'm in California. I hate they he'll have an entirely different college experience than mine. I'm angry at my parents for not having enough money to have kept my little brother a sheltered, spoiled kid who would never dream of joining the Air Force. I hate that my mother will be alone at home, worrying day and night about him - she already cries when I drive up the coast to UCSB.</p>
            <p>I hate that I've already had two dreams about my brother getting hurt. Could there be anything worse than loosing your only sibling? Then again, I like that Kevin is about to live out his dream of playing football on national television. I like that he'll be happy with the discipline and hard work and regimen of the academy. I know he'll like the location and scenery and fresh air - he always has.</p>
            <p>Maybe I don't quite know if I like it or hate it. On one hand he'll be living out his dream, but what about my mom's dream? I know that all she cares about is being close to her family. And what about me? Why should I be the one who's brother could get shipped off over seas at any moment? I'm not sure... all I know is that I love Kevin.</p>
        </div>
        <div id="6" class="writing">
            <h3>Lecture on PTSD</h3>
            <h4>By Dr. Sharon Rapp</h4>
            <hr>
            <p>I learned many things this quarter, one of the most insightful has been hearing on multiple occasions about the effects of PTSD. The more ignorant me of a few months ago thought of PTSD as too vague to warrant serious attention. I grouped it in with something along the lines of ADD. I believe there is a negative stereotype associated with both disorders due to the general abuse of the terms in society. It seems that every one of my friends has ADD, especially around finals week where taking prescription medication is all too accepted. There is a similarity in the use of the words 'traumatic' and 'post traumatic stress'. I've heard all too often about someone having a 'traumatic event' when they narrowly avoided a bumper collisions on the way to class. </p>
            <p>Of course, I've read about PTSD, and the Gulf War Syndrome and have read account of older men and women suffering years after and event. But this class seems to have driven it home for me. The combination of first hand accounts by Wilson and Jim and Dr. Rapp's guest lecture on Post Traumatic Stress Disorder has familiarized me with the disorder.</p>
            <p>I find Psychology fascinating, and the fact that grown men have both physical and mental side effects of events from decades ago is tough to truly comprehend. Having a legitimate authority figure in Dr. Rapp speaking of her knowledge and about Wilson's specific case was an eye opener and excellent introduction into the entire field of Veteran care and rehabilitation. The most interesting part of the lecture, and one of my favorites of the entire course, was Dr. Rapp's dialog with Wilson. It made everyone in the class appreciate how open the speakers are with us strangers.</p>
            <p>I wonder how much effort, at a federal level, goes into proper rehabilitation of returning war veterans. Such rehabilitation extends past physical wounds and into long-term psychiatric care. Dr. Rapp seemed to really care about assimilating veterans into a more comfortable lifestyle and outlook. Again, the most shocking part of their stories must be their young age.  For all this to happen at such a yong age and have them return home to their same age group...which remained mostly static while others were at war really shook them up. Just as I have changed <em>dramatically</em> in the few short years since leaving for college, Wilson and Jim came back entirely different. I wonder how close in touch the men who returned remained in the first few weeks home. I try to image myself in their shoes, and things must have been so strange after the initial excitement of returning home slowly wore off. </p>
            <p></p>
            <p></p>
        </div>
        <div id="7" class="writing">
            <h3>PTSD</h3>
            <h4><em>Achilles in Vietnam</em> - Jonathan Shay</h4>
            <hr>
            <p>This course was the only true 'life science' I had the pleasure of taking this quarter. The rest of my time is spent studying Economic theory or programming web application at work. Most of the things I'm very good at are hard, quantitative studies. With clear path to learn difficult concepts, and expected results. All of this breaks down when examining people. I believe the human mind is the last great frontier (maybe technology and space as well) left mostly unexplained. So any time a course tries to explain human behavior, whether its with logical reasoning in economics or chemical reactions in bio psychology, I am intrigued. The entire topic of PTSD has intrigued me from the start of the quarter.</p>
            <p>In trying to tie the course to our readings, Jonathan Shay's <em>Achilles in Vietnam</em> proves to be an easy choice. I most enjoyed Shay's take on the psychological analysis of PTSD, which seemed to reinforce some of the things Dr. Rapp spoke of. The violence, physical deprivation, and combat that the young men experience must have been very difficult to endure, but the physical wound don't seem to be the most difficult to overcome. The grand confusion of the veteran's is what really stuck with me.</p>
            <p>Many that went off to war came from a military family, and were set to follow in the footsteps of their father/grandfather. Their ancestors fought brave, important battles and their sacrifices helped shape the United States of America. The Vietnam veterans were robbed of such acclaim. All gave at least some sort of serious sacrifice in Vietnam, and upon returning they were looked down upon by the public, friends, and sometimes even their own family. Shay writes about a Veteran whose experiences reinforce this fact, and Jim even refused to acknowledge his own status as a veteran on some occasions (job seeking).</p>
            <p>As I mentioned in the pros of my brother going off to the Air Force, comradarity is a very powerful and sought after thing. Shay draws a parallel between Achille's relationship with Patroclus and the close bond that war Veterans experienced. Immediately, I thing of Jim's love for Charlie and the devastation is caused him when he lost Charlie. Loosing someone who takes care of you must be incredibly scary. My roommate, who recently lost his father, has shared with me the loss of certainty and support - the backbone to his life - and how it has changed him for better and for worse. These personal accounts are how knowledge is truly spread. And thats why this class has been so incredibly insightful, because all the literature is anchored by the real life accounts of Jim and Wilson.</p>
        </div>
        <div id="8" class="writing">
            <h3>Letter to My Brother</h3>
            <h4>Love you mate</h4>
            <hr>
           <p>Kevin,</p>
            <p>In the next few months you’ll experience a dramatic change in every aspect of your life.  When you get on the plan to Air Force this summer, you’ll begin the next chapter of your life. You won’t have any money, good food, or close friends and you’ll once again be a freshman – the new guy who doesn’t know much. However, you will have one –very important – thing. You’ll know that you earned your spot at that academy and on that team.  You’ll know that you earned the respect of hundred of people back home, most importantly your family. And you’ll know that from now on, and for the first time, every decision you make will be your own. From now on, every time you decide to wake up early, study longer, or work harder you’ll have the amazing satisfaction of know that it was your choice.</p>
            <p>Life is a series of decision little bro, and so far you’ve been making the right ones. All I ask is that in the next year (and for the rest of your life) you keep an open mind to everything this life has to offer. I hope you fall in love with your school, your classes, and your football team. You’ll have two hardworking parents and an older brother who are willing to sacrifice anything to help you. Realize that I just want to have a little brother who is happy and safe. </p>
            <p>You were born more intelligent than most people, but more importantly – you’ve grown up to be harder working than anyone I know. Work harder than the next guy, stay happy, and keep in touch with the people who really do care about you.</p>
        <p>Go Falcons</p>
        <p>- Mike</p>

